body:
@987Nabil Let's clean this up while we're at it. Zippable only existed because Combiner was not around at the time; Combiner subsumes Zippable. Also I don't like the names or optionality of the unleft / unright.

Here's a sketch at what I'm looking at:

<html><head></head><body><h1>Tuples, Eithers, and Unions: Algebraic Type Class Guide</h1>
<h2>Overview</h2>
<p>Three families of type classes that provide <strong>combining</strong> (constructing compound types from simpler ones) and <strong>separating</strong> (decomposing compound types into simpler ones). Both operations <strong>canonicalize</strong> their output, meaning input does not need to be in canonical form — canonical structure is a postcondition of every operation, not a precondition on inputs.</p>

Family | Structure | Canonical Form | Example
-- | -- | -- | --
Tuples | Products | Flat tuple | (A, B, C, D)
Eithers | Tagged sums | Left-nested Either | Either[Either[Either[A, B], C], D]
Unions | Untagged sums | Flat union | A \| B \| C \| D


<p><strong>Canonicalization algorithm (compile-time):</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Inspect the right branch of the Either.</li>
<li>If the right branch is <code>Either[X, Y]</code>, reassociate: <code>Either[L, Either[X, Y]]</code> becomes <code>Either[Either[L, X], Y]</code>.</li>
<li>Repeat until the right branch is atomic.</li>
<li>Recurse into the left branch to ensure it's also canonical.</li>
</ol>
<h3>Unions: Flat Canonical Form (Scala 3 only)</h3>
<p><strong>Canonical form:</strong> <code>A | B | C | D</code> — a flat union with no nested unions (though at the type level, Scala 3 unions are inherently flat and associative, so canonicalization is mostly about the Separator's runtime discrimination order).</p>
<p><strong>Separation convention:</strong> The rightmost type member is peeled off, consistent with Tuples and Eithers.</p>
<hr>
<h2>Macro Sketches</h2>
