Would it be simple enough to use a set in `Format` that can be added to? Or would it make sense to use a global/local registry of equivalence relationships that can then be used to determine the root Format for a mime type?

For example, tracking relationships in disjoint sets would allow for expressive inheritance rules:

```scala


// Define a format with multiple MIME types
object JsonFormat extends TextFormat[JsonCodec](
  Set("application/json", "text/json", "application/vnd.api+json"),
  JsonDeriver
)

final class MimeTypeRegistry private (
  private val parent: mutable.Map[String, String],
  private val rank: mutable.Map[String, Int],
  private val formatMap: mutable.Map[String, Format]
) {

  /**
   * Registers a format with its supported MIME types.
   * All MIME types for the same format will be grouped together.
   */
  def register(format: Format): MimeTypeRegistry = {
    val mimeTypes = format.mimeTypes.toList
    if (mimeTypes.nonEmpty) {
      // Initialize all MIME types as separate sets
      mimeTypes.foreach { mimeType =>
        if (!parent.contains(mimeType)) {
          parent(mimeType) = mimeType
          rank(mimeType) = 0
        }
        formatMap(mimeType) = format
      }

      // Union all MIME types for this format
      mimeTypes.tail.foreach { mimeType =>
        union(mimeTypes.head, mimeType)
      }
    }
    this
  }

  // disjoint set operations with path compression and union by rank
  private def find(mimeType: String): Option[String] = {
    parent.get(mimeType).map { p =>
      if (p != mimeType) {
        val root = find(p).getOrElse(p)  // recursively find root
        parent(mimeType) = root          // path compression
        root
      } else {
        mimeType  // This IS the root
      }
    }
  }
}

val registry = MimeTypeRegistry.empty

registry.register(JsonFormat) 
// registers `JsonFormat`s mime type relationships: "application/json" <<- [ "text/json" , "application/vnd.api+json" ]

registry.find("text/x-json")
// Some("application/json")

// Get all equivalent mime types
Format.getEquivalentMimeTypes("application/json") 
// Set("application/json", "text/json", "application/vnd.api+json", "text/x-json")
```

With a registry, you wouldn't have to list all aliases for each `Format` instance; for cases like "application/json", "text/json", a library level registry might make sense, but equivalence becomes more situational  when working with unofficial types like "application/x-custom".

I guess if you had a registry you would only need to store the root mime-type for each disjoin set

